node.text:
Skywatching tips for August.🤩 

Look up to see a “blue moon,” it'll be the third full Moon out of four this season, where normally each season only has three. This happens every two-and-a-half to three years, or as they say..."once in a blue moon."

You’ll be able to catch the best-known meteor shower of the year, the Perseids, mid-month, peaking on August 12. August is also perhaps the best time this year to enjoy viewing Jupiter and Saturn, as both planets reach opposition. 

"Opposition" is the term for when a planet is on the same side of the solar system as Earth, and directly opposite from the Sun. Around this time, the planet is visible from sunset to sunrise, and reaches its highest point in the sky around midnight. Opposition is also near the time Earth is closest to the planet, or planets in this case, so this is when they tend to look their biggest and brightest.

The scientific heart of the international water-monitoring satellite SWOT, which was assembled in the JPL Spacecraft Assembly Facility, is now in Cannes, France. There, engineers and techs will spend the next year integrating hardware with the rest of the instrument.
 
SWOT is a collaboration between NASA and the French space agency @cnes, with contributions from the @canadianspaceagency and @spacegovuk. This satellite will make global surveys of Earth’s surface water. By measuring its height, researchers can track the volume and location of the finite resource around the world. 
 
It is scheduled to launch in late 2022.

Here’s a closer look at one of the instruments @NASA’s Perseverance Mars rover is using to study the rocks and soil in its pristine environment.
 
Mounted on the "head" of the rover's long-necked mast, SuperCam features a rock-vaporizing laser, camera, and microphone that helps the rover seek organic compounds that could be related to past life on Mars. It can identify the chemical and mineral makeup of targets as small as a pencil point from a distance of more than 20 feet (7 meters).

node.text:
🌄 Cleaner air.
 
A study focused on the early months of the #COVID19 lockdowns found that lower emissions dropped global ozone levels to a place that policymakers thought would take at least 15 years to reach by conventional means, such as regulations. Nitrogen oxide emissions (NOx), which create ozone pollution, decreased 15% globally and as much as 50% locally.
 
Ozone protects us from destructive solar radiation when it’s high above Earth in the stratosphere. But closer to the ground, ozone has other lasting impacts. Ozone at the surface was estimated to cause 365,000 deaths globally in 2019 by damaging the lungs of vulnerable people, such as young children and those who have asthma. It also damages the breathing systems of plants, which is their ability to photosynthesize. That damage reduced plant growth and crop yields.
 
When the world began to go into lockdown, scientists were given a unique opportunity to study how human activity interacts with natural Earth system processes at regional and global levels. A team of researchers focused on the two main oxides of nitrogen: nitrogen oxide and nitrogen dioxide. They charted the chain of events from reduced fossil fuels burning during lockdowns to reduced local NOx emissions and finally to reduced global tropospheric ozone pollution. They found that the stricter lockdowns showed greater reductions in emissions.
 
The total result of the reduced NOx emissions was a 2% drop in global ozone – half the amount that the most aggressive NOx emission controls considered by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change were expected to produce over a 30-year period.
 
Researchers also used measurements of NOx, ozone and other atmospheric gases from five @NASA and @ESA Earth-observing satellites. They fed the observations into four numerical methods of atmospheric chemical reactions and weather, finding that changes in the models’ atmospheres matched the satellite observations and reproduced known increases and decreases in emissions as regions went in and out of lockdowns.

node.text:
✨
 
In June, the after-dark wonders bring us the constellation Scorpius, a Strawberry Moon, Saturn and Jupiter visible in the south at dawn, and a partial solar eclipse visible in the Northeastern U.S. 
 
And for more excitement this month, @NASA's Juno spacecraft is making its next close flyby over Jupiter, and this time it will also make a low-altitude flyby over the planet-sized icy moon Ganymede.

This is the first of several planned flybys of the Jovian moons – including icy Europa and volcanic Io – that Juno will make over the next couple years.
 
More on what to look up to at night: go.nasa.gov/34hp376

NISAR, a joint @NASA-@ISRO.IN Earth-observing mission, will track the subtle changes in our planet’s surface and spot warning signs of volcanic eruptions.

The satellite will monitor these changes in Earth’s surface over nearly the entire globe. This type of monitoring has not been done before with the high resolution in space and time that NISAR will deliver.

NISAR is set for launch no earlier than 2022.

Listen closely 👂

Do you hear that rhythmic humming? That’s #MarsHelicopter as heard from the SuperCam instrument’s microphone on the #Perseverance rover. It’s the first time a spacecraft on another planet has recorded sounds of a separate spacecraft. This was captured during Ingenuity’s ambitious fourth flight. The rumbling and occasional clipping sounds that can also be heard are the Martian winds. 

Scientists made the audio (recorded in mono) easier to hear by isolating the 84 hertz helicopter blade sound, reducing the frequencies below 80 hertz and above 90 hertz, and increasing the volume of the remaining signal. Some frequencies were clipped to bring out the helicopter’s hum, which is loudest when the helicopter passes through the field of view of the camera.

#Mars #SoundsOnMars #Ingenuity #OMGrobots #technology #space #exploration #NASA #JPL

node.text:
It’s May and with it comes a super “blood moon” eclipse! 
 
On May 26, a total lunar eclipse will happen during a supermoon, which is when the Moon is closest to Earth in its orbit. Lunar eclipses tend to have a reddish hue because of the way sunlight filters through Earth’s atmosphere. Because of that reddish color, lunar eclipses tend to be called “blood moons.”
 
The best viewing spots for this eclipse will be around the Pacific Rim—Australia, New Zealand, Eastern Asia, and the western parts of the Americas—though the rest of the U.S. will be able to see at least a partial eclipse.
 
One other major treat for May is that you’ll be able to see all of the rocky inner planets of our solar system with the naked eye. Starting on the 14th, gaze toward the west about a half hour after sunset, local time, to spot #Mercury, #Venus and #Mars. You’ll need an unobstructed view of the horizon. Good viewing spots include shorelines or high up on a mountain.
 
Click the link in bio for more #skywatching tips. go.nasa.gov/34hp376

The #JunoMission used its infrared #instrument during recent flybys of #Jupiter’s mammoth #Jovian #moon Ganymede.

This new view of the icy orb comes out a decade after the Juno spacecraft’s launch.🚀

Observations by the spacecraft’s Jovian Infrared Auroral Mapper (#JIRAM) instrument, which “sees” in #infrared light not visible to the human eye, provide new information on #Ganymede’s #icy shell and the composition of the #ocean of liquid water beneath.

Fun fact: Jupiter’s moon Ganymede is larger than the planet Mercury!

More on the latest map and 10 year #anniversary: go.nasa.gov/3iqSKNh (temporary link in bio)

While this looks like a pizza oven, we won't be making pies in space 🍕

What is exciting is that we're a few steps closer with the #EuropaClipper mission! The hardware for Europa Clipper is rapidly taking shape as engineering components and instruments are being prepared for delivery to the JPL Spacecraft Assembly Facility. In workshops and labs across the country and in Europe, teams are crafting the complex pieces that make up the spacecraft.

In the photo above, engineers at @NASAGoddard in Greenbelt, Maryland, prepare for a propellant tank to be inserted into the cylinder in the background. The cylinder is one of two that make up Europa Clipper’s propulsion module. (Credit: NASA/GSFC Denny Henry)

Targeted for a 2024 launch, Europa Clipper will explore Jupiter’s icy moon Europa.

Oceans Melting Greeland, @NASA’s six-year pioneering campaign studying how seawater melting glaciers impacts future sea-level rise, is beginning its final field expedition.

The OMG team will fly around the entire #Greenland coast in a specially modified DC-3 aircraft. From early August through early or mid-September, probes will be dropped from the plane into 300 targeted locations in front of #glaciers in the ocean. As the probes sink, they will transmit temperature and salinity readings by radio waves back to the plane until the probes hit the ocean floor.

#Data from the first five years of this pioneering campaign has improved researchers' understanding of what the ocean is doing to Greenland’s ice sheets.

Mars stereo – no speakers required.🚁

Color stereo images from #MarsHelicopter’s 10th flight reveal details of Jezero Crater’s “Raised Ridges.” The captivating geologic features intrigued our Perseverance rover science team even before the rover had landed on the Red Planet. Now, these 3D pics might provide the data they need to decide if said ridges are worth the drive for a closer look. 

Pictures were snapped by Ingenuity from its lofty perch at 40 feet (12 meters) up - a Mars-record altitude. Flight 10 had the rotorcraft following the most complex flight profile to date. Its scouting continues to help Perseverance on its future drives.

We’re getting ready for #MarsHelicopter’s 11th flight!
 
The rotorcraft will fly at an altitude of about 12 meters, traveling ~385 meters all while taking several photos. The move allows for future reconnaissance flights of a geologically intriguing area known as “South Seitah” for the #Perseverance #rover as it continues its search for signs of ancient microbial life. These scouting efforts also provide a unique viewpoint the rover could otherwise not have on #Mars.

node.text:
Skywatching tips for August.🤩 

Look up to see a “blue moon,” it'll be the third full Moon out of four this season, where normally each season only has three. This happens every two-and-a-half to three years, or as they say..."once in a blue moon."

You’ll be able to catch the best-known meteor shower of the year, the Perseids, mid-month, peaking on August 12. August is also perhaps the best time this year to enjoy viewing Jupiter and Saturn, as both planets reach opposition. 

"Opposition" is the term for when a planet is on the same side of the solar system as Earth, and directly opposite from the Sun. Around this time, the planet is visible from sunset to sunrise, and reaches its highest point in the sky around midnight. Opposition is also near the time Earth is closest to the planet, or planets in this case, so this is when they tend to look their biggest and brightest.

Fighting the good fight.

#Researchers on the RADR-Fire team at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory have been experimenting with #ECOSTRESS data as part of a new tool now being implemented for first responders like the U.S. Forest Service.

ECOSTRESS measures surface #temperature from the vantage point of the #ISS. @u.s.forestservice responders are using #maps created by researchers at the @pnnlab, who use the instrument’s data to track the movement of the Bootleg Fire and to identify proximity and potential damage to critical infrastructure.

In the visualization above, the areas in red represent the hottest pixels ECOSTRESS detected. The extreme heat in those areas indicates the fire front, or where resources are most needed.

More on how we’re working together to tackle wildfires: go.nasa.gov/2Vkwlry

A new #aerial record! 🚁 

With the #MarsHelicopter’s #flight success today, we crossed its 1-mile total distance flown to date. It targeted an area called “Raised Ridges,” named for its #geographic features. Flight 10 is #Ingenuity’s most complex flight profile yet, with 10 distinct waypoints and a new #record height of 40 feet (12 meters).

At the completion of its flight, the helicopter put down at its seventh #airfield – about 310 feet (95 meters) due west of its takeoff zone. Ingenuity’s total time in the air was ~165.4 seconds. Aerial scouting aids the #Perseverance #Mars #rover team in deciding what moves to make next.

Super-vision! 🤓

For 16 years, @NASA's Spitzer Space Telescope unveiled previously unknown parts of the universe with its infrared "eyes." The Great Observatory was used to study and discover objects in our own solar system to the edge of the universe: Distant galaxies, a new ring around Saturn, asteroids, exoplanets, stars, young planetary systems, interstellar dust, black hole disks and jets.
 
We're fans of the Great Observatory's legacy so we're adding it to our new exoplanets poster series. Download at the link in bio: https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/

We’re honored to show the President of Spain @sanchezcastejon and @mayorofla Eric Garcetti the work we do. Spain hosts and staffs one of NASA's Deep Space Network's complexes and contributed science instruments to @NASA’s Curiosity and Perseverance Mars rovers.

Our #DeepSpaceNetwork knows long-distance. Its three facilities are spaced equidistantly apart in Goldstone, #California; near Madrid, #Spain; and near Canberra, #Australia. Their strategic placements permit constant communication with deep space missions as our planet rotates. go.nasa.gov/3kG9Bx1 (link in bio)

#Space is a big place and working collaboratively is a sure way to take it on.
